-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Prove that for all positive reals $a,b,c,d$ the inequality $a^{2}/b + b^{2}/c + c^{2}/d + d^{2}/a \;\ge\; a + b + c + d$ holds. 2. [Key Idea] Apply Cauchy’s Engel form (also called Titu’s Lemma): $\displaystyle\sum \frac{x_i^{2}}{y_i}\ge\frac{(\sum x_i)^{2}}{\sum y_i}$. 3. [Proof] Using Titu’s Lemma with $(x_1,x_2,x_3,x_4)=(a,b,c,d)$ and $(y_1,y_2,y_3,y_4)=(b,c,d,a)$: $\displaystyle\frac{a^{2}}{b}+\frac{b^{2}}{c}+\frac{c^{2}}{d}+\frac{d^{2}}{a} \;\ge\; \frac{(a+b+c+d)^{2}}{\,b+c+d+a\,} \;=\; a+b+c+d.$ 4. [Conclusion] By Cauchy’s inequality, $a^{2}/b + b^{2}/c + c^{2}/d + d^{2}/a$ is always at least $a+b+c+d$, as desired.
